    {
        "type": "highlight",
        "timestamp": "2024-10-19T19:43:03.031000Z",
        "highlightedText": "Sneezing, a protective mechanism, is crucial for our body to expel particulates from the nose, providing a defense for our lungs. This process is triggered by a sneeze gene and involves a small compound in our nasal cavity that stimulates immune cells. This reaction sends signals to the hippocampus in the brain, leading to reflexive muscle contractions and a sneeze, aiding the immune system in virus protection.\n\nThe volume and sound of a sneeze are influenced by our respiratory system's structure, including lung volume and the shape and flexibility of vocal cords. Reflexive muscle contractions also determine the sneeze's speed. However, the sound of a sneeze isn't only biological; it's also shaped by cultural factors, psychological factors, and societal norms.\n\nDr. Mas Takashma suggests that keeping the mouth closed can reduce sneeze volume effectively. However, suppressing a sneeze can damage the nose and sinus surface. Despite societal pressures, it's crucial not to entirely suppress a sneeze for health reasons. Sneezing helps flush out old cells, and holding back a sneeze may cause more harm than good.",
